DIV2.P:
I Unfortunately got acquainted with Mat∣thew Mahony, a seman who belonged to the Ruby man of war, and in conversation with him, at my own lodgings, I and my comrades told him we had nipped ourselves to go to Jamaica; at which he desred me not to go away 'till the Friday ollowing; for if we would but  him in getting a man that was crazy into the man of war's oat, he sid the Captain would not only reward us with a bond of , but likewie protect us from the pes; which occond us on Tuesday to go ee the Captain: But not finding him at his lodgngs, went with the said Maony to the sign of the White Hart, in the College Green, and, as the landlord told us, the Captain ordered us what liquors and vctuals we pleased to call for. But we being afraid to go nigh the man of war's boat, acquainted the said Mhony with our doubts, and he immediately informed the Captain thereof; wh told us, to be under no dread, for it was not worth his while to lye in that man∣ner for three or four seamen; but he wanted to lay hold of a man who was a lunatic, and ruining himself, his amily, and him the said Captain; and that he wanted him on board


to keep him out of the lawyer's and affidavit men's hands; and promised that no harm should attend us on that account; and that he would not only give us a plentiful reward, but likewise protect us from all manner of press. That when the said gentleman came out of mr. Smith's house in the green, the Captain ordered us not to touch him, but to follow him, and see if he put up at any house in the city; which we did; but the gentle∣man continuing his journey without stopping we returned back; and, on our return, Ma∣hony went into the Coffee house near the Change, and spoke to the Captain, who told him we should have a better opportunity, and desired of us not to be out of the way. Accordingly we all met on the Sunday fol∣lowing, and waited in the Green 'till the gentleman came out of mr. Smith's, where he left the Captain behind him; and being encouraged by Mahony and others belong∣ing to the said Ship, we stopped him, and hauled him to the man of war's boat, being assisted by some of the crew. The Captain came prciently after us to the boat, where we left them, and returned to our lodgings, and staid there all night. In the morning fol∣lowing, before we were out of bed, Mahony and one Charles White came to out lodgings, and made us get up to drink punch, which we did; but seeing White have a quantity of gold, and Mahony have a gold watch, it made us imagine they had robbed the gentle∣man, and thereupon we went directly on board the man of war, to acquaint the Cap∣tain;


but when we came on board we found the Captain a prisoner for assisting in the death of the gentleman, and the Lieutenant, knowing that we helped to bring him to the boat, ordered us to be confined, where we remained for eight-days, 'till the Mayor sent for us, who, after examining us, committed us to Newgate, where we now remain.
